<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>

<section xml:id="sec-examples-algebras" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
  <title>Some examples of algebras</title>
  <example>
    <title>Associative ring as <m>\Z</m>-algbera</title>
    <statement>
        <p>
            Every associative ring <m>A</m> can be considered as a <m>\Z</m>-algebra.
        </p>
    </statement>
    
  </example>
  <example xml:id="ex-ring-over-itself">
    <title>Ring as an algebra over itself</title>
    
    
    <statement>
        <p>
            Let <m>R</m> be a commutative ring with unity. Then <m>R</m> can be considered a right <m>R</m>-module using the multiplication in ring <m>R</m>. With this considerations, <m>R</m> is an <m>R</m>-algebra.
        </p>
    </statement>
  </example>
  <example xml:id="ex-algebra-over-center">
    <title>Ring over its center</title>
    
    
    <statement>
        <p>
            Suppose that <m>A</m> is a ring (not necessarily commutative), and let <m>Z(A)</m> be the center of <m>A</m>. Then <m>A</m> is a <m>Z(A)</m>-algebra.
        </p>
    </statement>
  </example>
  <example xml:id="ex-matrix-algebra">
    <title>Matrix algebra</title>
    
    
    <statement>
        <p>
            Suppose that <m>R</m> is a commutative ring and <m>n</m> is a positive integer. Suppose that <m>A</m> is an <m>R</m>-algebra. Then the ring of <m>n\times n</m> matrices over <m>A</m>, denoted by <m>M_n(A)</m>, is an <m>R</m>-algebra.
        </p>
    </statement>
  </example>
  <example xml:id="ex-endomorphism-algebra">
    <title>Endomorphism algebra</title>
    
    
    <statement>
        <p>
            Let <m>R</m> be a commutative ring with unity. Suppose that <m>M</m> is a right <m>R</m>-module. The endomorphism ring <m>\End{R}{M}</m> is an <m>R</m>-algebra. 
        </p>
    </statement>
  </example>
  <example xml:id="ex-polynomial-algebra">
    <title>Polynomial ring as algebra</title>
    
    <statement>
        <p>
            Let <m>R</m> be a commutative ring with unity. The polynomial ring <m>R[X]</m> is an <m>R</m>-algebra.
        </p>
    </statement>
  </example>
  <example xml:id="ex-oppositive-algebra">
    <title>Opposite algebra</title>
    
    
    <statement>
      <p>
        Let <m>R</m> be a commutative ring, and let <m>A</m> be a right <m>R</m>-algebra. We denote by <m>A^{op}</m> the opposite ring of <m>A</m>. Recall that <m>A^{op}</m> as a set is equal to <m>A</m>. Furthemore, it satisfies the following relations for any <m>a^{op},b^{op}\in A^{op}</m>.
        <me>
          a^{op}+b^{op}=(a+b)^{op},\quad\text{and}\quad a^{op}b^{op}=(ba)^{op}
        </me>
         Then <m>A^{op}</m> is a right <m>R</m>-algebra, called the opposite algebra of <m>A</m>, gievn by the scalar multiplication
        <me>
          a^{op}\cdot r=(a\cdot r)^{op} \quad\text{for any }r\in R\text{ and }a^{op}\in A^{op}.
        </me>
      </p>
    </statement>
  </example>
  <p>
    We discuss the example of <sq>Group algebra</sq> in the next section.
  </p>
</section>
